<br>
I'm not a big fan of alignment systems; while they can be good guidelines for stereotypes, worlds with objective moralities have serious metaphysical problems. That's why there's such debate as to the nature of good, evil, light, and dark in the game -- is that Paladin who viciously slays all Teir'Dal good? What about the Teir'Dal cleric who carefully tends the wounds of all who follow Innoruuk? Who defines the objective good and evil? While it's possible for those sorts of worlds to work (especially if the &quot;objective&quot; rules are hidden, have nothing to do with classic good and evil, or are out of sync with the societies of the world), they tend to have issues in their simplest forms.<br>
<br>
IMHO, all the advantages of alignments can be provided with well-written lore and factions (both in the EQ sense and the IC sense of the world). <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.realitywerks.com/hosted-images/elludensig.png" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
